of this name are descended from Abraham Venables, who came to VA from England in or before 1687."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Venables was born in 1400, in Kinderton, Cheshire, England, his father, Thomas de Venables, was 33 and his mother, Blanche De Arderne, was 25. He married Ellen Daniels. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died about 1427, in Middlewich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1400–about 1427":"1400–umbes 1427","1395–1455":"1395–1455","1400–1427":"1400–1427","1400–1465":"1400–1465","1427–1491":"1427–1491","1427–Male":"1427–Surnud","1433–1486":"1433–1486","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1375–1459":"1375–1459","1459":"1459","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","about 1427":"umbes 1427","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1491":"1491","1427":"1427","Middlewich, Cheshire, England":"Middlewich, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leighton, Cheshire, England":"Leighton by Neston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kinderton, Cheshire, England":"Kinderton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1400–about 1427":"1400–noin 1427","1395–1455":"1395–1455","1400–1427":"1400–1427","1400–1465":"1400–1